BLUETONGUE, BOVINE, OVINE - BELGIUM, NETHERLANDS
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Sun 20 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Nieuwsblad, Belgium, 19 Aug 2006 [translated from Flemish by
Mod. AS abridged, edited]
<http://www.nieuwsblad.be/Article/Detail.aspx?ArticleID=DMF19082006_063>

There is a high probability that bluetongue, detected Thursday (17
Aug 2006) in the Netherlands and Saturday (19 Aug 2006) also in
Belgium, has been present in the region for a longer period. The
disease infects initially cattle before manifesting itself
[clinically] in sheep. This has been said by the Dutch minister of
agriculture Cees Veerman in a letter sent Friday [18 Aug 2006] to the
parliament.
Cattle do not become sick by the infection but serve as carriers of
the bluetongue virus [BTV] and thus as source for further infection.
"According to the literature, cattle are the 1st animals to get
infected; this means that in [the Dutch province of] Limburg, a large
number of cows might have already been infected," says the minister.
Veerman also had good news. He notified the parliament that "it is
highly unlikely that the disease will survive the winter in the
Netherlands; this is related to the fact that the vector is not
active during the winter months, enabling the livestock to recover,"
said the minister. He emphasized that control measures are not
necessarily directed at the early eradication of the disease, but at
limiting the losses.
In the meantime, the farmers organization "LTO-south" reported that
the vector is, probably, not a south-European midge [_Culicoides
imicola_, - Mod. AS] but a "usual" local midge [For reference, see
commentary]. This information was related to the LTO-south by
researchers from the university of Wageningen. The midges might have
become infected with BTV by feeding on an infected imported animal,
transmitting it further to other ruminants.
So far, the disease has been confirmed in 3 farms in Limburg: one in
Kerkrade and 2 in Nuth. [A map showing both places is available at
<http://www.multimap.com/map/browse.cgi?lat=50.9178&lon=5.8847&scale=500000&icon=x>].
It is suspected in 13 other farms. In Belgium, the disease has been
confirmed, so far, in 11 farms in the province Luik [Liege] and in
the Voeren region [a hilly region within the Belgian province
Limburg, south of Maastricht; see clickable map at
<http://www.supertravelnet.com/maps/index.php?action=showmap&country=116_9005_5&language=1>.
- Mod.AS].
On Monday [21 Aug 2006], veterinary experts from 25 member states of
the EU will meet in Brussels to discuss the issue. They might decide
to extend the zones, where no transport of animals is allowed, to 50
or even 100 km [around disease foci]. Within these zones,
vaccinations may be applied.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Although no BT cases have been detected (so far?) in neighboring
Germany, its North-Rhine Westphalia state has implemented animal
movement restrictions, similar to the measures in the Netherlands and
Belgium. See map at
<http://www.mediendatenbank.nrw.de/mediadatabase/bt-nl-suspected-170806_2.jpg>.
- Mod.AS]
